Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Competency hearing on November 17, 2022 at 02:30 pm.

(2:28 PM cases 20CF633, 21CF400, 21CF904, 22CF497, 22CF529 called.) Defendant Charles B. Fitzhenry in court. Attorney Ryan Glenn Kohler appeared on behalf of Attorney Karl Schmidt in court for Charles B. Fitzhenry. Prosecuting attorney Tiffany M. Winter in court for the State of Wisconsin. 
State advises the day after the examiner contacted the mental health facility, the defendant was present in Eau Claire as there was police contact and the defendant was hospitalized.
Court inquires with the defendant if the competency hearing is rescheduled, will the defendant appear and cooperate to complete the examination. Defendant advises the Court he will cooperate.
Court finds good cause to extend the time frame for completing the competency examination.
Defendant updates address and phone number with the Court.
Competency Hearing in cases 20CF633, 21CF400, 21CF904, 22CF497, 22CF529 scheduled for November 17, 2022 at 2:30 pm (1/2 hour) in person.
Dated 10/04/2022, Letter from Ryan Stepp, Psy.D., to Court regarding status of competency evaluation.
Order for Competency Examination by DHS.
Proposed Order for Competency Examination by DHS
Competency hearing on October 13, 2022 at 10:30 am.

(Cases called at 1:35 PM - 22CF497 and 22CF529)
Defendant Charles B. Fitzhenry in court with Attorney Karl A Schmidt. Attorney Tiffany M. Winter in court for State of Wisconsin.
Preliminary hearing held on case 22CF497 first.  State calls Officer Bridget Coit to the stand - sworn and testifies.  Court takes judicial notice of bonds in 21CF904, 20CF663, and 21CF400.  Cross-examination by Defense.  Officer Coit is excused.  Court finds there was probable cause that a felony (bail jumping) was committed - Counsel to schedule further proceedings in Branch 5.  
As to case 22CF529, State calls Officer Derek Jack to the stand - sworn and testifies.  Court takes judicial notice of bonds in the previously listed cases.  Cross-examination by Defense.  Officer Jack steps down.  Court finds probable cause that the felony bail jumping was committed by the Defendant in this case - matter bound over for further scheduling with Branch 5.
